{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611829"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:16:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16245"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16245"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.25,0.15,0.15,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82188"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8936"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16245"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67386"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21265"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82188"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPhysiological differences of circulating substances can vary between neonates and adults.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is physiologically lower in neonates compared to adults?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alkaline phosphatase","Total bilirubin","Calcium","Magnesium","Phosphate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of normal physiological differences in laboratory values between neonates and adults. \u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium\u003C/strong\u003E levels are physiologically lower in neonates compared to adults due to reduced reabsorption in the immature kidney. This typically normalises over the first few weeks of life as renal function matures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlkaline phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E is significantly higher in neonates and children compared to adults due to increased osteoblastic activity during periods of rapid bone growth. Levels can be 2-3 times the adult reference range.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal bilirubin\u003C/strong\u003E is also higher in neonates, particularly in the first week of life, due to physiologic jaundice. This results from increased red blood cell breakdown, immature hepatic conjugation, and increased enterohepatic circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium\u003C/strong\u003E levels are typically higher in neonates compared to adults, particularly in the first 24-48 hours of life. This is due to the sudden cessation of placental calcium transfer at birth triggering parathyroid hormone release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphate\u003C/strong\u003E levels are also higher in neonates and children compared to adults, reflecting the increased needs for bone mineralisation during periods of rapid growth.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neonatal magnesium levels are physiologically lower than adult levels due to reduced reabsorption in the immature kidney.","Neonatal alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin are typically higher than adult levels due to bone growth and physiologic jaundice respectively."],"references":["Ostrander B, Bardsley T, Korgenski EK, Greene T, Bonkowsky JL. Neonatal Magnesium Levels Between 24 and 48 Hours of Life and Outcomes for Epilepsy and Motor Impairment in Premature Infants. Pediatr Neurol. 2016 Jun;59:41-6. doi: 10.1016/j.pediatrneurol.2016.02.012. Epub 2016 Mar 3. PMID: 27025188; PMCID: PMC4912928.","Rigo J, Pieltain C, Christmann V, Bonsante F, Moltu SJ, Iacobelli S, Marret S. Serum Magnesium Levels in Preterm Infants Are Higher Than Adult Levels: A Systematic Literature Review and Meta-Analysis. Nutrients. 2017 Oct 16;9(10):1125. doi: 10.3390/nu9101125. PMID: 29035309; PMCID: PMC5691741.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67386"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16245"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67386"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-28T17:18:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-28T17:18:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8936"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82188"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","positio